%I A277433 #44 Jul 09 2026 00:27:41
%S A277433 1,4,4,4,6,6,8,8,8,8,10,10
%N A277433 Martin Gardner's minimal no-3-in-a-line problem, all slopes version.
%C A277433 a(n) is the minimal number of counters that can be placed on an n X n grid, no three in a straight line, such that adding one more counter on any vacant grid point will produce three in a line. Lines can have any slope.
%C A277433 The "queens" version of this problem, where lines are restricted to vertical, horizontal and diagonal, is A219760.
%C A277433 a(11) <= 10, a(12) <= 10. Resolved as equalities by Aichholzer, et al. - _Ed Pegg Jr_, Jul 03 2026
%C A277433 To a(30), upper bounds are 1, 4, 4, 4, 6, 6, 8, 8, 8, 8, 10, 10, 12, 12, 14, 14, 15, 16, 16, 16, 16, 18, 20, 20, 22, 24, 24, 24, 24, 25. Dmitry Kamenetsky supplied a(16), a(17) and a(21). Aichholzer paper provided a(20), a(21), a(22), a(30). Best known coverings and variants at the Pegg link. - _Ed Pegg Jr_, Jul 03 2026
%H A277433 O. Aichholzer, D. Eppstein and E.-M. Hainzl, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.13170">Geometric Dominating Sets</a>, Comput. Geom. Theory Appl., 108 (2023), Art. 101913.
%H A277433 Achim Flammenkamp, <a href="https://wwwhomes.uni-bielefeld.de/achim/no3in/readme.html">The No-Three-in-Line Problem</a>, personal page at University of Bielefeld, since 1992.
%H A277433 Robert Israel, <a href="/A277433/a277433_1.pdf">Examples for n <= 12</a> (provably optimal for n <= 10).
%H A277433 Sandi Klavžar, James Tuite, and Ullas Chandran, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.19385">The General Position Problem: A Survey</a>, arXiv:2501.19385 [math.CO], 2025. See p. 39.
%H A277433 Ed Pegg Jr, <a href="https://community.wolfram.com/groups/-/m/t/3740214">The Min and Max of the No-3-in-line problem</a>, Jun 26 2026.
%e A277433 For n = 1 and n = 2, one cannot have 3 in a line, so there must be no vacant grid point (otherwise it's not a solution because adding a counter there would be possible without 3 in a line), whence a(n) = n^2.
%e A277433 For n = 3, one can see that filling any 2 X 2 block with a(3) = 4 counters is a solution, and one can check that there is no solution with only 3 counters.
%e A277433 For n = 4, filling either the 2 X 2 central squares, or just the 4 corners, no counter can be added without producing 3 in a line. Again, one can check that there is no valid solution with only 3 counters, so a(4) = 4.
%Y A277433 Cf. A219760.
%Y A277433 Cf. A000769 (the maximum no-3-in-a-line problem).
%K A277433 nonn,more
%O A277433 1,2
%A A277433 _Robert Israel_, Oct 14 2016
%E A277433 a(11)-a(12) from _Ed Pegg Jr_, Jul 03 2026
